{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487503"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"361"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/361"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.44,0.08,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114837"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/361"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96837"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"356"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6461"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44615"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114837"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 70-year-old man attends for a urological assessment of his lower urinary tract symptoms of increasing urinary frequency, nocturia, poor stream and terminal dribbling. He has had these symptoms for about a year and they do not trouble him unduly as he only has to get up once at night to void. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his bladder is not clinically distended. A digital rectal examination is performed, showing soft enlargement of both lateral lobes of the prostate. Investigations show that he does not have any evidence of urinary infection and his renal function and PSA are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Annual assessment","Tamsulosin","Finasteride","Transurethral resection of the prostate","Prazosin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man\u0027s young age and soft prostatic enlargement on examination make benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) the most likely cause for his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn any patient with bladder neck outflow obstruction whose symptoms are not interfering with their quality of life, there is no evidence to suggest that any form of medical or surgical intervention will improve matters. More importantly, the side effects of these therapies might outweigh any potential gains, making \u003Cstrong\u003Eannual assessment\u003C/strong\u003E the most appropriate course of action. In this case, the man\u0027s symptoms do not bother him unduly and so a more conservative approach should be taken. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis symptoms can be formally gauged and tracked over time using the International Prostate Symptom Score (IPSS). In the meantime, some lifestyle/behavioural changes can be made including double voiding before bed and reducing night time fluid and diuretic (eg. tea, coffee, alcohol) consumption to reduce nocturia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrazosin\u003C/strong\u003E is a first generation selective alpha-1-adrenergic receptor antagonist, while \u003Cstrong\u003Etamsulosin\u003C/strong\u003E is of the second generation, both acting to relax smooth muscle around the bladder neck and prostatic urethra. Tamsulosin has a more favourable adverse effect profile while prazosin is avoided in those with hypertension, using antihypertensives and with impaired blood pressure regulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFinasteride\u003C/strong\u003E is a 5-alpha-reductase inhibitor, working to reduce prostate volume, reduce symptoms, and prevent progression of BPH. If symptoms are refractory to monotherapy, combination medications eg. tamsulosin-finasteride can be attempted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransurethral resection of the prostate\u003C/strong\u003E (TURP) would be indicated if moderate-severe symptoms are present and refractory to medical therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Understanding the step-wise management in men with benign prostate hyperplasia.","Understanding the mechanism of action of common medications used to treat lower urinary tract symptoms in men."],"references":["Langan RC. Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia. Prim Care. 2019 Jun;46(2):223-232."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96837"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"361"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96837"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:48:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:48:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"361"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114837"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap